{{Merge|Robert Kerr (MP)|date=April 2018}}
[[File:1st Earl of Ancram.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Robert Kerr, 1st Earl of Ancram by [[Jan Lievens]]<ref>[http://www.nationalgalleries.org/collection/online_az/4:322/result/0/8758?initial=L&artistId=2993&artistName=Jan%20Lievens&submit=1 Jan Lievens portrait of Robert Kerr] in the [[National Galleries of Scotland]]</ref>]]
'''Robert Kerr (or Carr), 1st Earl of Ancram''' (c. 1578–1654), was a Scottish nobleman and writer.

==Biography==
He descended from a third son of Sir Andrew Kerr of Ferniehurst, and entered public life as laird of Ancrum in [[Roxburghshire]]. He was born about 1578, and succeeded to the family estate in 1590 on the death of his father, who was assassinated by his kinsman, Robert Key, younger of Cessford. He was cousin to [[Robert Carr, Earl of Somerset|Robert Carr]], the [[favourite]] of [[James I of England|James VI]]. Kerr appears to have also been honoured at an early age with court favour. Soon after the king’s accession to the English throne, Kerr occupied a considerable station in the household of [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. The household of that time  was more splendid and consisted of more people than the present royal household. He subsequently was employed by [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]], who became his patron through life. Charles mediated a match between Sir Robert and the [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Lady Anne Stanley]], daughter of the [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]].<ref name=Chambers-1840-315>Chambers (1840), [https://books.google.com/books?id=0iopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA315#v=onepage&q=&f=false p. 315]</ref>

In 1620, Kerr was involved in a fatal quarrel with a young man named Charles Maxwell, who insulted him without provocation as he entered the palace at [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]]. In a duel that followed, Sir Robert killed Maxwell. Even though Maxwell's friends acquitted Kerr of blame, the king's strict rules for prevention and punishment of duels forced him to flee to Holland, where he remained about a year. During his exile, he collected pictures, for which, like his royal master, he had good taste. He eventually presented those he brought back with him to the prince. He was also distinguished by his literary taste.<ref name=Chambers-1840-315/>

On the accession of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] to the throne, in 1625, Sir Robert Kerr was made a [[gentleman of the bedchamber]], and on 24 June 1633, when the king was in Scotland at his coronation, he was elevated to the peerage, under the titles of [[Earl of Ancram]] and [[Lord Kerr of Nisbet, Langnewton, and Dolphinstoun]]. Previously, his son William, by his first wife Elizabeth, daughter of Sir John Murray of Blackbarony, had married his relative, Anne, [[Marquess of Lothian|Countess of Lothian]] in her own right, and had been, by the king, endowed with full participation in that title. It was therefore arranged, in the patent granted to Kerr, that his own title should descend to the children of his second marriage. Thus, he was father of two peers.<ref>Chambers (1840), pp. 315, 316</ref>

Unlike others who owed everything to this prince, the Earl of Ancram remained the prince's steady adherent during the whole of his troubles—though he was unable to prevent his eldest son, the [[William Kerr, 3rd Earl of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]], from acting a conspicuous part on the opposite side. On the death of Charles, Kerr took refuge in Holland, where he spent the remainder of his days in solitary afflictions and poverty, and died in 1654, in the seventy-sixth year of his age. [[Jan Lievens]] painted him marvelously. His son [[Charles Carr, 2nd Earl of Ancram|Charles]], inherited his title, but ultimately merged with that of Lothian.<ref name=Chambers-1840-316>Chambers (1840), p. 316</ref>

==Family==
He had two sons by his first marriage to Elizabeth Murray:
: Stanley Kerr (d. bef. May 1672){{citation needed|date=March 2010}}
: [[William Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian]](bef. 1615&nbsp;– c. October 1675)

He had one son and two daughters by his second marriage to [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Anne]], daughter of [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby]]:{{citation needed|date=March 2010}}
: [[Charles Kerr, 2nd Earl of Ancram]] (August 6, 1624&nbsp;– September 1690)
: Vere Kerr
: Elizabeth Kerr

